<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>When milk is stagnant, the
pressure in the ducts of the mammary gland increases and part of the milk is
released into the surrounding tissues.&nbsp;The immune system can view breast
milk as a foreign agent and trigger inflammation.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:normal'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Infection.&nbsp;The infectious process most often develops against
the background of lactostasis.&nbsp;Bacteria enter through cracked nipples or
milk ducts.&nbsp;Normally, breast milk contains lactobacilli and opportunistic
microorganisms, however, if the mother has chronic infections, such as
tonsillitis, pyelonephritis, bacteria can penetrate into the breast tissue
during pregnancy, when the immune system was weakened.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Non-lactational mastitis is
chronic and is divided into two types</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:normal'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Periductal mastitis.&nbsp;A rather rare pathology.&nbsp;It is
characterized by inflammation of the ducts that are located under the nipple
and areola.&nbsp;The exact cause of its occurrence is unknown.&nbsp;Most often
it affects young women, although it can occur in men as well.&nbsp;Smoking
plays an important role in the development of this type of mastitis.&nbsp;Toxic
substances from tobacco smoke are thought to damage duct tissue and cause
inflammation.&nbsp;Then an infection joins the already damaged ducts, which can
lead to the formation of purulent inflammation and an abscess.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>In women over 45 years of age,
periductal mastitis takes the form of ductal ectasia.&nbsp;As a result of
age-related hormonal changes, normal duct tissue is replaced by connective
tissue, becomes thicker, and a greenish liquid appears in the ducts.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:normal'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Idiopathic granulomatous mastitis.&nbsp;A rare disease, most often
occurs in women who have given birth.&nbsp;The cause of its occurrence is
unknown.&nbsp;It is characterized by the development of non-infectious
inflammation in the breast tissue.</span></p>

